00:00:00.930 --> 00:00:06.569
At the centre of our societies is a hugely
inventive force dedicated to nudging us towards

00:00:06.569 --> 00:00:12.650
a heightened appreciation of certain aspects
of the world. With enormous skill, it throws

00:00:12.650 --> 00:00:18.490
into relief the very best sides of particular
places and objects. It uses wordsmiths and

00:00:18.490 --> 00:00:24.160
image makers of near genius, who can create
deeply inspiring and beguiling associations

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:30.500
and position works close to our eyelines at
most moments of the day. Advertising is the

00:00:30.500 --> 00:00:37.800
most compelling agent of mass appreciation
we have ever known. Because advertising is

00:00:37.800 --> 00:00:43.290
so ubiquitous, it can be easy to forget that
– of course – only a very few sorts of

00:00:43.290 --> 00:00:48.930
things ever get advertised. Almost nothing
in the world is in a position to afford the

00:00:48.930 --> 00:00:55.149
budgets required by a campaign; advertising
is a form of love overwhelmingly reserved

00:00:55.149 --> 00:01:02.059
for those wealthy potentates of modern life:
nappies, cereal bars, conditioners, hand sanitisers

00:01:02.059 --> 00:01:09.720
and family sedans. This has a habit of skewing
our priorities. One of our major flaws as

00:01:09.720 --> 00:01:15.150
animals, and a big contributor to our unhappiness,
is that we are very bad at keeping in mind

00:01:15.150 --> 00:01:21.210
the real ingredients of fulfilment. We lose
sight of the value of almost everything that

00:01:21.210 --> 00:01:26.479
is readily to hand, we’re deeply ungrateful
towards anything that is free or doesn’t

00:01:26.479 --> 00:01:32.159
cost very much, we trust in the value of objects
more than ideas or feelings, we are sluggish

00:01:32.159 --> 00:01:38.090
in remembering to love and to care – and
are prone to racing through the years forgetting

00:01:38.090 --> 00:01:44.550
the wonder, fragility and beauty of existence.
It’s fortunate, therefore, that we have

00:01:44.550 --> 00:01:50.810
art. One way to conceive of what artists do
is to think that they are, in their own way,

00:01:50.810 --> 00:01:57.200
running advertising campaigns; not for anything
expensive or usually even available for purchase,

00:01:57.200 --> 00:02:03.220
but for the many things that are at once of
huge human importance and constantly in danger

00:02:03.220 --> 00:02:08.259
of being forgotten. In the early part of the
twenty-first century, the English artist David

00:02:08.259 --> 00:02:11.741
Hockney ran a major advertising campaign for
trees. image03

00:02:11.741 --> 00:02:13.319
