00:02:13.319 --> 00:02:17.689
At the start of the sixteenth century, the
German painter Albrecht Dürer launched a

00:02:17.689 --> 00:02:20.680
comparable campaign to focus our minds on
the value of grass.

00:02:21.140 --> 00:02:27.620
And in the 1830s, the Danish artist Christen
Kobke did a lot of advertising for the sky,

00:02:27.620 --> 00:02:30.880
especially just before or after a rain shower.

00:02:31.640 --> 00:02:36.459
In the psychological field, the French painter
Pierre Bonnard carried out an exceptionally

00:02:36.459 --> 00:02:42.060
successful campaign for tenderness, turning
out hundreds of images of his partner, Marthe,

00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:45.440
viewed through lenses of sympathy, concern
and understanding.

00:02:46.120 --> 00:02:50.700
In an associated move, the American painter
Mary Cassatt made a pretty good case for the

00:02:50.700 --> 00:02:54.160
world-beating importance of spending bits
of one’s life with a child.

00:02:55.420 --> 00:03:01.760
These were all acts of justice, not condescension.
They were much needed correctives to the way

00:03:01.760 --> 00:03:08.280
that what we call ‘glamour’ is so often
located in unhelpful places: in what is rare,

00:03:08.280 --> 00:03:15.609
remote, costly or famous. If advertising images
are to blame for instilling a sickness in

00:03:15.609 --> 00:03:21.290
our souls, the images of artists are what
can reconcile us with our realities and reawaken

00:03:21.290 --> 00:03:26.900
us to the genuine, but too-easily forgotten
value, of particular bits of our lives. Consider

00:03:26.900 --> 00:03:32.400
Chardin’s Woman Taking Tea. The sitter’s
dress might be a bit more elaborate than is

00:03:32.400 --> 00:03:37.629
normal today; but the painted table, teapot,
chair, spoon and cup could all be picked up

00:03:37.629 --> 00:03:43.769
at a flea market. The room is studiously plain.
And yet the picture is glamorous – it makes

00:03:43.769 --> 00:03:50.010
this ordinary occasion and the simple furnishings,
seductive. It invites the beholder to go home

00:03:50.010 --> 00:03:55.839
and create their own live version. The glamour
is not a false sheen that pretends something

00:03:55.839 --> 00:04:01.329
lovely is going on when it isn’t. Chardin
recognises the worth of a modest moment and

00:04:01.329 --> 00:04:05.460
marshalls his genius to bring its qualities
to our notice.

00:04:06.060 --> 00:04:12.660
It lies in the power of art to honour the
elusive but real value of ordinary life. It

00:04:12.660 --> 00:04:19.310
may teach us to be more just towards ourselves
as we endeavour to make the best of our circumstances:

00:04:19.310 --> 00:04:25.319
a job we do not always love, the imperfections
of age, our frustrated ambitions and our attempts

00:04:25.319 --> 00:04:31.730
to stay loyal to irritable but loved families.
Art can do the opposite of glamourise the

00:04:31.730 --> 00:04:38.840
unattainable; it can reawaken us to the genuine
merit of life as we’re forced to lead it.

00:04:38.840 --> 00:04:42.960
It is advertising for the things we really
need.

